 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1127<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/30/02 7:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=546.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's your stance on a chemical HLV?</span><hr size=1> True.  Consider the difficult time (and huge expense) they are having building a station at 400 kilometers.  <br>
<br>
Now try to build something with existing boosters that requires an additional booster to place in in it's final orbit, tens of thousands kilometers away!  The final payload is so much smaller it's almost worthless... of course a reusable 'space tug' could help, but what is really needed is a HLV.  Even resurrecting the Energia booster would be an improvement over the SST. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 228<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/30/02 1:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=546.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's your stance on a political graft space program?</span><hr size=1> I think we're responding more to the whole idea of NASA doing the entire thing. Most reservations to this topic are more or less directed at the lack of faith in the congresionally authorized bureaucracy, intended solely to benefit the military/industrial complex.<br>
<br>
It's known that the motivation for the International Budget Buster (ISS) is not to build a functional, useful station in LEO.<br>
 There's no need to design any new HLV to build a useful station. Kick out the bureaucracy, hang the congress-critters who hamstring the program when it doesn't benefit the campaign financing industrialists in their districts enough, let in some reasonable engineers with communications with the corporate interests who have expressed realistic interests in an orbiting R&amp;D engineering park, and watch it go.<br>
 A Shuttle-C puts up the Skylab volume in one go, (and here's the important bit) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> without the money-hog excess of the labor involved in refurbishing the Shuttle orbiter</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
Paying that army of ground crew is the true purpose of the IBB, and why it's running too expensive, and not effective as a LEO station.<br>
<br>
 There's nothing new needed, except bending metal to fit the books &amp; stacks &amp; libraries of engineering studies backing up the ET station &amp;/or Shuttle-C designs (both called the most studied &amp; evolved concepts in space travel history).<br>
<br>
 Granted, it would be nice to see something as big as a Sea Dragon station volume. The simple fact is that there are ways to profit in space, to the point that new HLVs aren't the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> first thing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> needed. Get a venture going, one which is dsigned with K.I.S.S. firmly in mind, and with upgrades and serviceability more important than initial complexity to benefit the largest possible number of contractors.<br>
 Money being made in space lets the effective cost of getting payload up in a Shuttle-C come down to reasonable levels.<br>
<br>
 You don't need to put up several hundred tons in one shot to make a space industrial park, or even a SPS or space colony producing factory. (Topic search @ <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://permanent.com">permanent.com</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->: Bootstrapping).<br>
Once there's enough interest in things going on in space, newer ways of getting to orbit will evolve.<br>
 (I'm still leaning towards small VTO rocketplanes for getting crew into orbit. Nothing else offers as much safety. A HTO spaceplane -either 1 or 2STO? You're going to sit on that mountain of fuel, with no way to get away from it in a hurry?)<br>
<br>
