<br>
 I wondered why, in the Ares HLV, the SSMEs were canted off-center; some little amount of thrust is lost.<br>
<br>
 The answer is similar to why the Shuttle-C, and why it's favorable to the Ares:<br>
 The <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://science.ksc.nasa.gov/shuttle/technology/sts-newsref/stsover-prep.html#stsover-fss">launch facilities</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> are configured for the Shuttle, so the flame deflectors and trenches are set up for it. Several hundred million dollars would be needed for a new launch complex or to modify the trenches and sound suppression and service structures on the existing pads.<br>
 The Shuttle-C is favorable, as it is right now for this reason, and because it requires nothing new at all, except for a simpler, dumber sideways mounted cargo pod (compared to the Shuttle orbiter itself). The Ares requires some work on the ET, to handle thrust directly on the ET instead of from the remote mountings for the orbiter, and the mass of the cargo on top instead of lashed alongside.<br>
<br>
 I wonder how much work has been done on launching HLVs like this, or Energia derived similar things, from floating rigs like old oil rigs at sea. Little hassle, since the rig can be evacuated and launch control run from a nearby ship.<br>
 Maybe a toss-up over whether it's easier/cheaper to get launch support from Kennedy which is already set up to launch Shuttles, or to do everything to get a rig or use the Arianne facilities or somewhere else.<br>
<br>
 One thing I particularly like (and a particularly damning indication of the fact that NASA doesn't <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> want</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to do things the easy way), is the idea of using a modified ET station volume with a Shuttle-C.<br>
 NASA doesn't want to launch their Shuttle orbiters with any modification to the ET. This is supposedly the entirety of the reasoning for why the ET station hasn't flown. (Yeah, yeah, some loss of cargo -though in some cases the orbiter can carry <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> more</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> cargo if the ET is taken all the way up- because of the extra mass of the modified ET. None of this matters if you use Shuttle-C)<br>
 OK.<br>
 Toss the orbiter to the side of a hangar somewhere, attach a cargo pod to the side of a modified ET (wet-launch station), and send up your huge station volume, with 40 tons of cargo which will be used on the first EVA to fit it out.<br>
 The first EVA attaches stabilising/boosting ED tethers and solar panels, power conditioning and waste heat radiators, O2/H2 scavenging equipment for the 6 tons left over in the tank, and the airlock/doors to allow workers to get inside the empty tank with interior fittings.<br>
 Another shuttle-C carries up additional interior finishing stuff (deck sections, furnishings, whatever) and voila! In 4 launches (including the final EVA which leaves the first crew) you've got a station for less than the cost of 3 Shuttle launches (much <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> much</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> less if you use Soyuz for the crewed launches).<br>
<br>
No, that doesn't spend enough money among enough congressional districts' contractor companies. Doesn't pay the payroll of the Shuttle's ground crew.<br>
